Re: Verb modifies Noun
by Fillanzea » Wed 11.11.2009 12:21 am When you say that romaji can't express ふ, all that really means is that an English speaker without previous knowledge of Japanese wouldn't pronounce either "fu" or "hu" as the correct sound. But there's no way for an English speaker without previous knowledge of Japanese to pronounce ふ　correctly, with or without romaji, so that seems like a moot point. It's only from an Anglo-centric point of view that it matters that ふ　isn't pronounced with an English "h" or "f" sound -- mapping "fu" to the sound "ふ" isn't really any harder or more arbitrary than mapping "fu" to the sound in "food" or "fool."
Kotoba-gari: intermediate-to-advanced Japanese reading and vocabulary
